# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-greek-warfare
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abonoteichos] Abonoteichos was a town on the coast of Paphlagonia, memorable as the birthplace of the infamous fortuneteller Alexander Abonoteichites, founder of the cult of Glycon, of whom Lucian left an amusing account in the treatise bearing his name.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abonoteichos] According to Lucian, Alexander petitioned the Roman emperor (probably Antoninus Pius) that the name of his native place should be changed from Abonoteichos to **Ionopolis**; and whether the emperor granted the request or not, we know that the town was called Ionopolis in later times.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abonoteichos] Not only does this name occur in Marcian of Heraclea and Hierocles, but on coins of the time of Antoninus and Lucius Verus we find the legend Ionopoliton (ΙΩΝΟΠΟΛΙΤΩΝ), as well as Abonoteichiton (ΑΒΩΝΟΤΕΙΧΙΤΩΝ).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abonoteichos] The modern Turkish name İnebolu is evidently a corruption of Ionopolis.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abonoteichos] It was the site of a 2nd-century AD temple of Apollo.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abonoteichos] It was important enough in the Roman province of Paphlagonia to become a suffragan bishopric of the Metropolitan of its capital Gangra, but faded later.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abonoteichos] The diocese was nominally revived as a Latin Catholic titular bishopric under the name Ionopolis, which was spelled **Jonopolis** in the Roman Curia (besides Italian *Gionopoli*) from 1929 to 1971.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The *Abora I* originated as a school project in Germany using locally grown Giant (Miscanthus).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] All subsequent vessels were commissioned to boat builders from the Aymara nation living at Lake Titicaca in Bolivia; the same boat builders worked already for Thor Heyerdahl.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] As building material they used the very sturdy and durable Totora reed which is far better suited for this purpose.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The Abora (or Abora I, in retrospective) was designed, built and used between 1996 and 1999.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] It sailed from Alghero (Sardinia, Italy) to Piombino (Tuscany, Italy).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The Abora II sailed in 2002 across the Mediterranean: from Alexandria (Egypt) to Beirut (Lebanon), Cyprus and back to Alexandria.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] It thus became the first modern-time reed boat which managed to complete an extended round trip and then to return to the port of departure.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The departure at Alexandria coincided with the inauguration of the Bibliotheca Alexandrina, the new Alexandrian library; the Abora crew brought some gifts (books) from Thor Heyerdahl's Kon-Tiki Museum in Oslo, Norway in honor of the inauguration.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Thor Heyerdahl had also personally supported the preparation of the Abora I and II expeditions; by coincidence the launch of the Abora II took place on 18 April 2002, which turned out to be the day when Thor Heyerdahl died.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] With Abora III, Dominique Görlitz attempted the first ever crossing of the Atlantic from West to East with a reed boat.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Görlitz considered it possible that such events actually took place in antiquity.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] As a motivation, he particularly quoted the finding of traces of cocaine and nicotine in Egyptian mummies, including chopped tobacco leaves and the remains of a Mexican tobacco beetle in the mummy of Ramses II (1298–1213 BC).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Mainstream scholars have shown that there are possible Old World sources of cocaine and nicotine.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The finding of tobacco leaves became a popular topic in fringe literature and the media and it was seen as proof of contact between Ancient Egypt and the New World.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Compared to an East-West crossing, which Thor Heyerdahl successfully demonstrated in 1970 with the barely maneuverable reed boat Ra II, a west-east crossing of the Atlantic is much more difficult.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] This must be done further north along the Gulf Stream.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] However, the Gulf Stream does not flow evenly, but forms huge eddies.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Furthermore, the winds there blow inconsistently from all directions.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] This means that this crossing cannot take place as a practically pure drift, as in the case of the Ra II in the opposite direction, rather the reed boat must be able to cover longer distances by wind even under adverse conditions.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The hull of the boat was again manufactured in Bolivia (in 2006).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The boat was finalized one year later in New York.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The *Abora III* expedition started in New York on July 11, 2007.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] An initially supportive Azores high dissolved completely in early August, and the crew faced one storm after another.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Two of these storm lows reached hurricane strengths with wind speeds of up to 51 knots.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] These bad weather fronts affected the Abora III, but did not yet lead to serious damage.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] However, three side swords broke during the first storm, but this happened close enough to the American mainland that replacement swords could be delivered and replaced.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] In mid-August, after 500 km of a total of around 6000 km, a calm delayed the trip.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] A three-day hurricane then damaged the rear of the Abora III on August 27, 2007 in such a way that it had to be separated from the hull. during the subsequent 4 days, the crew reinstalled the intact rudder and moved the mast further towards the bow.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The modified Abora III could temporarily set full sail and even sail up to 90° to the wind.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] On September 4, the next storm with wind force 10 severely affected both the Abora III and an escort vessel approaching from the Azores.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Therefore, the crew abandoned the experiment on September 5, 2007, about 900 kilometres from the Azores, the 11-member crew and switched to the escort vessel.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The reed boat was left to the sea after cutting the strings that held the hull together.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] A message in a bottle thrown into the water before the boat was evacuated was found in the Bahamas in October 2010.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] This illustrates that a West-East crossing of the Atlantic requires an intact sailing ability of the boat (in contrast to the opposite direction: Thor Heyerdahl's Ra II was also badly damaged in 1970, but was still able to drift to America with the help of the Canary Current).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The aim of the Abora IV expedition was to retrace possible trade contacts between the Black Sea and the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Herodotus mentioned in his *Histories* trading contacts between the Egyptians and the Caucasus on the eastern Black Sea coast; according to him, especially metals were imported into Egypt via this route.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] According to the expedition leader Dominique Görlitz's assumption, tin and amber were also exported from Central Europe to Egypt via the Balkans and finally the Black Sea to the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Varna in Bulgaria was chosen as the starting point of the expedition both because of the place's historic significance (Varna Necropolis) and for practical reasons; the expedition received strong support from the Varna Archaeological Museum.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The final construction took place from May to August 2019 in Beloslav near Varna.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Due to the late delivery of the prefabricated reed bundles from Bolivia and due to extremely bad weather conditions in Bulgaria, the launch of the Abora was greatly delayed and the start of the expedition could only take place on August 16.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The Abora IV sailed through the Black Sea to Istanbul in Turkey, then through the Bosporus (on tow, for safety reasons), through the Marmara Sea and into the Dardanelles (again on tow) to Çanakkale (a modern harbor near ancient Troy), then onward into the Aegean Sea.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Here, the first station was the Greek island of Limnos, where the vessel managed to enter and to leave the prehistoric port of Poliochni without being supported by a tug boat.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] From there, it sailed on to Santorini, hereby managing to pass several straits between several Greek islands.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] During the expedition, Dominique Görlitz received the offer from the Turkish Ministry of Culture in Ankara to exhibit the reed boat in the Patara Archeology Park (near Antalya) as a permanent exhibit.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Thereupon it was decided to sail from Santorini straight to Kaş (a modern harbour near Patara) at the Lycian coast.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Here, the Abora IV arrived on 19 September; the entire distance from Varna to Kaş was covered in 34 days.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] As planned, the vessel is now on permanent display on the agora of the ancient city of Patara.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Like most experimental-archaeological projects, also the ABORA projects could only examine the technical feasibility of a proposed method.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Whether these methods were indeed exploited in the past, can only be clarified by archaeological finds.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The Abora expeditions specifically acclaimed to have reproduced an ancient navigation technology based on the use of leeboards.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] The expedition leader Dominique Görlitz presented various examples of such depictions (with and without leeboards) in his books and on the official project website.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Ethnological evidence for the use of large navigable rafts exists only from South America, where such rafts were in use also after the Spanish conquest.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] These rafts used so-called centerboards or guaras; they could be navigated even without a rudder.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Also Thor Heyerdahl conducted already some experiments using those guaras.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Therefore, Heyerdahl followed the ABORA expeditions with great interest until his death in 2002.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Positive appraisals of the ABORA projects came also from various other scientists, for instance Havva Iskan (Akdeniz University, Turkey, lead archaeologist at Patara, where the ABORA IV is now on permanent display).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] In 2007, during the ABORA III expedition, a critical article appeared in the German popular-scientific journal *Spektrum der Wissenschaft*.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] It quotes a German Egyptologist who doubts Görlitz' interpretation of details of boat depictions as leeboards, as well as his assumptions with regard to the age of those depictions, but does not offer an alternative explanation.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abora-expeditions] Specifically with regard to the Abora III expedition (attempt of a West-East Atlantic crossing), doubts are also expressed about alleged evidences for tobacco or cocaine use in ancient Egypt.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Acarnania's foundation in Greek mythology was traditionally ascribed to Acarnan, son of Alcmaeon.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The name of Acarnania appears to have been unknown in the earliest times.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Homer (8th century BC) only calls the country opposite Ithaca and Cephalonia, under the general name of "Epeirus" (῎ηπειρος), or the mainland, although he frequently mentions the Aetolians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The country is said to have been originally inhabited by the Taphii (or Teleboae), the Leleges, and the Curetes.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Taphii, or Teleboae were chiefly found in the islands off the western coast of Acarnania, where they maintained themselves by piracy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Leleges were more widely disseminated, and were also in possession at one period of Aetolia, Locris, and other parts of Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Curetes are said to have come from Aetolia, and to have settled in Acarnania, after they had been expelled from the former country by Aetolus and his followers.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The name of Acarnania is derived from Acarnan, the son of Alcmaeon, who is said to have settled at the mouth of the Achelous.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] If this tradition is of any value, it would intimate that an Argive colony settled on the coast of Acarnania at an early period.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] In the 7th century BC, Greek influence in the region became prominent when Corinth settled Anactorium, Sollium and Leucas, and Kefalonia settled Astacus.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The settlements of Alyzeia, Coronta, Limnaea, Medion, Oeniadae, Palaerus, Phoitiai and Stratus are also mentioned by Thucydides, this latter city being the seat of a loose confederation of Acarnanian powers that was maintained until the late 1st century BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The ancient Acarnanians, however, were Greeks, and as such were allowed to contend in the great Pan-Hellenic games, although they were closely connected with their neighbors, the Agraeans and Amphilochians on the Ambracian Gulf, who were barbarian or non-Hellenic nations.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Like other rude mountaineers, the Acarnanians are praised for their fidelity and courage.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] They formed good light-armed troops, and were excellent slingers.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] They lived, for the most part, dispersed in villages, retiring, when attacked, to the mountains.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Strabo relates that they were united, however, in a political League (the Acarnanian League), of which Aristotle wrote an account in a work now lost (Ἀκαρνάνων Πολιτεία).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Thucydides mentions a hill, named Olpae, near the Amphilochian Argos, which the Acarnanians had fortified as a place of judicial meeting for the settlement of disputes.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The meetings of the League were usually held at Stratus, which was the chief town in Acarnania; but, in the time of the Romans, the meetings took place either at Thyrium, or at Leucas, the latter of which places became, at that time, the chief city in Acarnania.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] At an early period, when part of Amphilochia belonged to the Acarnanians, they used to hold a public judicial congress at Olpae, a fortified hill about 3 miles (4.8 km) from Argos Amphilochicum.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Of the constitution of their League, we have scarcely any particulars.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] We learn from an inscription found at Punta, the site of ancient Actium, that there were a council and a general assembly of the people, by which decrees were passed: Ἔδοξε τᾷ βουλᾷ καὶ τῷ κοινῷ τῶν Ἁκαρνάνων.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] At the head of the League, there was a strategus (Στρατηγός) or general; and the council had a secretary (γραμματεύς), who appears to have been a person of importance, as in the Achaean and Aetolian Leagues.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The chief priest (ἱεραπόλος) of the temple of Apollo at Actium seems to have been a person of high rank; and either his name or that of the strategus was employed for official dates, like that of the first Archon at Athens.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Because it is located strategically on the maritime route to Italy, Acarnania was involved in many wars.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Acarnanians espoused the cause of the expelled Amphilochians, and in order to obtain the restoration of the latter, they applied for assistance to Athens.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Athenians accordingly sent an expedition under Phormio, who took Argos, expelled the Ambraciots, and restored the town to the Amphilochians and Acarnanians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] An alliance was now formally concluded between the Acarnamians and Athenians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The only towns of Acarnania which did not join it were Oeniadae and Astacus.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Acarnanians were of great service in maintaining the supremacy of Athens in the western part of Greece, and they distinguished themselves particularly in 426 BC, when they gained a signal victory under the command of Demosthenes over the Peloponnesians and Ambraciots at the Battle of Olpae.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] At the conclusion of this campaign they concluded a peace with the Ambraciots, although they still continued allies of Athens.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] In 391 BC we find the Acarnanians engaged in war with the Achaeans, who had taken possession of Calydon in Aetolia; and as the latter were hard-pressed by the Acarnanians, they applied for aid to the Lacedaemonians (Spartans), who sent an army into Acarnania, commanded by King Agesilaus.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The latter ravaged the country, but his expedition was not attended with any lasting consequences, whilst the cities of Acarnania surrendered to the Lacedaemonians under Agesilaus, and continued to be Spartan allies for a time, they joined the Second Athenian League in 375 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Acarnanians later sided with the Boeotians in their fight against Sparta, and with Athens against Philip II of Macedon at Chaeronea.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] After the time of Alexander the Great, in 314 BC, at the behest of the Macedonian king Cassander, the settlements of Acarnania lying near the Aetolian border were conglomerated into fewer, larger settlements.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Still, border conflicts with the Aetolians were frequent, and led to Acarnania's territory being partitioned between Aetolia and Epirus in, c.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] After the fall of the king of Epirus, the Acarnanian territory that had been given to Epirus regained its independence, and Leucas became the capital of the region, but conflict with the Aetolians remained.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The Acarnanians in consequence united themselves closely to the Macedonian kings, to whom they remained faithful in their various vicissitudes of fortune.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] They refused to desert the cause of Philip in his war with the Romans, and it was not till after the capture of Leucas, their principal town, and the defeat of Philip at the Battle of Cynoscephalae that they submitted to Rome.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] When Antiochus III king of Syria, invaded Greece, 191 BC, the Acarnanians were persuaded by their countryman Mnasilochus to espouse his cause; but on the expulsion of Antiochus from Greece, they came again under the supremacy of Rome.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] In the settlement of the affairs of Greece by Aemilius Paulus and the Roman commissioners after the defeat of Perseus (168 BC), Leucas was separated from Acarnania, and the city of Thyrreion was appointed the new capital.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] In the 1st century BC, Acarnania suffered greatly at the hands of pirates, and in Roman civil wars.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] When Greece was reduced to the form of a Roman province, it is doubtful whether Acarnania was annexed to the province of Achaea or of Epirus, but it is mentioned at a later time as part of Epirus.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The inhabitants of several of its towns were removed by Augustus to Nicopolis, which he founded after the Battle of Actium, and Acarnania fell under that city's rule; and in the time of Augustus emperor the country is described by Strabo as utterly worn out and exhausted.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] In 395, it became part of the Eastern Roman Empire.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] When the empire was attacked by Western powers in the Fourth Crusade (1204), Acarnania passed to the Despotate of Epirus and in 1348 it was conquered by Serbia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Then in 1480 it fell to the Ottoman Empire.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Acarnania is composed of three main regions: 1) a rocky coastline, 2) a rugged strip of mountain range that follows the coastline, and 3) plains lying between these mountains and the Achelous River.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Anciently, Acarnania was reckoned the most westerly province of Greece, bounded on the north by the Ambracian Gulf, on the northeast by Amphilochia, on the west and southwest by the Ionian Sea, and on the east by Aetolia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] It contained about 1,571 square miles (4,070 km2).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Under the Romans, or probably a little earlier, the river Achelous formed the boundary between Acarnania and Aetolia; but in the time of the Peloponnesian War, the territory of Oeniadae, which was one of the Acarnanian towns, extended east of this river.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The interior of Acarnania was covered with forests and mountains of no great elevation.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Between these mountains there are several lakes, and many fertile valleys.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The chief river of the country is the Achelous, which in the lower part of its course flows through a vast plain of great natural fertility, called after itself the Paracheloitis.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] By the 19th century, the plain was covered with marshes, and the greater part of it appeared to have been formed by the alluvial depositions of the Achelous.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Owing to this circumstance, and to the river having frequently altered its channel, the southern part of the coast of Acarnania has undergone numerous changes since antiquity.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The chief affluent of the Achelous in Acarnania is the Anapus (Ἄναπος), which flowed into the main stream 80 stadia south of Stratus.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] There are several promontories on the coast, but of these only two are especially named by writers in antiquity, the promontory of Actium and that of Crithote (Κριθωτή), on the west coast, forming one side of the small bay, on which the town of Astacus stood.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Of the inland lakes, the only one mentioned by name by the classical writers is that of Melite (Μελίτη; the modern Lake Trichonida), 30 stadia long and 20 broad, north of the mouth of the Achelous, in the territory of Oeniadae.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] There was a lagoon, or salt lake, between Leucas and the Ambracian gulf, to which Strabo gives the name of Myrtuntium (Μυρτούντιον).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Although the soil of Acarnania was fertile, it was not much cultivated by the inhabitants.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The products of the country are rarely mentioned by the ancient writers.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] Pliny speaks of iron mines, and also of a pearl-fishery off Actium.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] The chief wealth of the inhabitants consisted in their herds and flocks, which pastured in the rich meadows in the lower part of the Achelous.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnania] There were numerous islands off the western coast of Acarnania.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The **Acarnanian League** (Ancient Greek: τὸ κοινὸν τῶν Ἁκαρνάνων, *to koinon tōn Akarnanōn*) was the tribal confederation, and later a fully-fledged federation (*koinon*), of the Acarnanians in Classical, Hellenistic, and early Roman-era Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The League existed since the 5th century BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] It was at the time not a fully-fledged federation (*sympoliteia*) as elsewhere in Greece, but a loose confederation of the Acarnanian cities.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] An assembly of representatives met at Stratos, having also the power of negotiating treaties with other states, a supreme court existed at Olpae (in common with the Amphilochians), and there was a common coinage and cult, but no federal officials and no common foreign policy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanians agreed to provide 2,000 hoplites in the common struggle against Philip II of Macedon, but as the latter occupied Ambracia, only a handful volunteers participated alongside the southern Greek city-states in the Battle of Chaeronea.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] As a result, the leaders of the independence faction were banished, and the League became a member of the League of Corinth organized by Philip.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] During Alexander the Great's campaign in Asia, the Aetolians seized the town of Oiniadai from the League.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] With the exception of Alyzia, the Acarnanians remained largely uninvolved in the struggles that followed the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BCE, but in 314 BCE Cassander arrived in Acarnania and reorganized the League on a truly federal basis.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The island of Leucas joined the League soon after, following the eviction of its Macedonian garrison.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanian League was a member of the Hellenic League organized by Demetrius Poliorcetes, and then became subject to King Pyrrhus of Epirus.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] 270 BCE, the Acarnanians and Aetolians settled their differences, agreeing on the Acheloos River as their mutual border, and concluded a perpetual alliance.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The treaty specified the obligations of mutual military assistance, and the two leagues assured each other the rights of *epigamia*, citizenship, and acquisition of property.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] This treaty records seven *strategoi* (one each from Oiniadai, Derion, Stratos, Phoitia, Thyrreion, Anaktorion and Leucas), a hipparch (from Oiniadai), a foreign secretary (from Oiniadai), and a treasurer (from Stratos).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The frequent occurrence of officials indicates that at the time it was the most important city of the League.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] According to Polybius, however, soon after the Aetolians allied themselves with Pyrrhus' son.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] Alexander II of Epirus, and invaded Acarnania, dividing the country between them: the northern part with Leucas went to Epirus, and the south was incorporated into the Aetolian League.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] Following the extinction of the Aeacid dynasty in Epirus, in 230 BCE the Acarnanian League was reconstituted in the northern, former Epirote part of the country.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] Leucas was its capital, and only Anaktorion, Palairos, Thyrreion, and Medion were members.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] Allied with the Illyrians, and then with the Macedonians and the Achaean League, in the Social War (220–217 BCE) the Acarnanians were able to recover Phoitia and Oiniadai.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] This success did not last long: in the First Macedonian War (214–205 BCE), Oiniadai was lost again, and in the Second Macedonian War (200–197 BCE) the Acarnanians were forced to capitulate to the Roman Republic, who however left them in their possessions and free to govern themselves.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] Oiniadai was returned after the Roman–Seleucid War.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] Despite their steadfast loyalty to Rome, the League lost Leucas after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BCE), as it became an autonomous state, but Thyrreion became a member.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] The Acarnanian League continued to exist even after the final establishment of Roman power over Greece in 146 BCE.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/acarnanian-league] It was only after the Battle of Actium in 31 BCE that the League was incorporated into the Roman province of Achaea.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The **Achaean League** (Ancient Greek: Κοινὸν τῶν Ἀχαιῶν, romanized: *Koinon ton Akhaion*, lit.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] 'League of Achaeans') was a Hellenistic-era confederation of Greek city-states on the northern and central Peloponnese.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The league was named after the region of Achaea in the northwestern Peloponnese, which formed its original core.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The first league was formed in the fifth century BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Although the first Achaean League is much less well documented than its later revival, it maintained a recognizable federal structure through the early Hellenistic period, but later fell into a period of dormancy under growing Macedonian influence.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The more famous second Achaean League was established in 280 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] It allied with Antigonid Macedon at the Cleomenean War, Social War and First Macedonian War against the Aetolian League and Sparta.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Its most successful leader was Philopoemen who forced Sparta to join the League.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The league allied with the Roman Republic during the Second Macedonian War and the Aetolian War.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The Achaean War led to the League's conquest and dissolution by the Romans in 146 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The League represents the most successful attempt by the Greek city-states to develop a form of federalism, which balanced the need for collective action with the desire for local autonomy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Through the writings of the Achaean historian and statesman Polybius, this structure has had an influence on the constitution of the United States and other modern federal states.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The first Achaean League became active in the fifth century in the northwestern Peloponnese.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Its earliest organizational structure remains partly obscure, but new evidence has illuminated aspects of its government.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] A fragmentary inscription discovered at Aegium, dating to the fourth or possibly the very beginning of the third century BC, attests to a developed federal system that included a *boule* (federal council) and a board of *damiourgoi* (federal magistrates).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The ancient capital of the league was Helike, but after the catastrophic destruction of that city by an earthquake and tsunami in 373 BC, Aegium subsequently assumed that role.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Xenophon's *Hellenica* reports that Achaea underwent a democratic revolution in 367 and the previous ruling class was exiled.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Although it was once widely claimed that Alexander the Great dissolved the Achaean League in 324 BC, the passage in Hypereides (*Against Demosthenes* 18) supposed to reference such a dissolution is now widely understood to be too ambiguous to support that interpretation.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The idea is further undermined by the continued political activity of Achaea and Arcadia during the Lamian War, when they refused to join the Greeks while Boeotia did support Antipater.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The league continued to exist into the early Hellenistic period and is attested in 302 BC, when the Achaeans were listed among the members of the League of Corinth revived by Demetrius Poliorcetes.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] In the years following, Macedonian influence intensified in some Achaean cities while others became ruled by tyrants.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] This period of increasing external control appears to have been linked to Demetrius’ change in policy, signalled by his capture and fortification of Athens in 294 BC, with the planting of garrisons in Achaean cities likely occurring shortly thereafter.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Polybius records that during this time, tyrannies were established in cities such as Ceryneia and Bura, and a garrison was stationed at Aegium.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Despite this interference, there is no indication that the Achaean League was formally dissolved.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Historian Jakob Larsen suggests that the confederacy's federal institutions effectively ceased to operate because so many of its member cities were under external control.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] This state of suspension allowed the league to resume its functions later without the need for significant constitutional changes, suggesting that some mutual understanding among the cities facilitated its reactivation when conditions allowed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The regional Achaean League was revived in 281/0 BC by the communities of Dyme, Patrae, Pharae and Tritaea, joined in 275 by Aegium, which controlled the important sanctuary of Zeus Homarios.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The league grew quickly to include the entire Achaean heartland, and after a decade it had ten or eleven members.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The key moment for the League's transformation into a major power came in 251, when Aratus, the exiled son of a former magistrate of Sicyon, overthrew the tyranny in his native city and brought it into the Achaean League.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Since the Sicyonians were of Dorian and Ionian origin, their inclusion opened the League for other national elements.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Aratus, then only twenty years old, rapidly became the leading politician of the League.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] In the thirty two years between 245 and his death in 213, Aratus would hold the office of general a total of sixteen times.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] At this time, Central Greece and the Peloponnese were dominated by the Macedonian Kingdom of Antigonus II Gonatas who maintained garrisons at key strategic points such as Chalcis, Piraeus and Acrocorinth, the so-called "fetters of Greece".
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] In other cities of the Peloponnese, namely Argos, Orchomenus, and Megalopolis, Antigonus had installed friendly rulers who were perceived as tyrants by the Achaeans.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Aratus, whose father had been killed by one, called for the liberation of these cities and secured financial support for the League from Ptolemy II of Egypt, an enemy of the Antigonids.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] He then used the money to challenge the Macedonian hold on the Peloponnese.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Aratus' greatest success came when he captured Corinth and the fortress of Acrocorinth in 243 BC in a daring night attack.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] This effectively blocked Macedonian access to the Peloponnese by land, isolating their allies at Megalopolis and Argos.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] In light of this success, a number of Greek communities, including Epidaurus and Megara joined the League and Ptolemy III increased Egypt's support for the Achaeans, being elected as the League's *hegemon* (leader) in return.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Antigonus Gonatas finally made peace with the Achaean League in a treaty of 240 BC, ceding the territories that he had lost in Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The increased size of the league meant a bigger citizen army and more wealth, which was used to hire mercenaries, but it also led to hostility from the remaining independent Greek states, especially Elis, the Aetolian League and Sparta, which perceived the Achaeans as a threat.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Corinth was followed by Megalopolis in 235 BC and Argos in 229 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] However the league soon ran into difficulties with the revived Sparta of Cleomenes III.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Aratus was forced to call in the aid of the Macedonian King, Antigonus III Doson, who defeated Cleomenes at Sellasia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Antigonus Doson re-established Macedonian control over much of the region.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] In 220 BC, the Achaean League entered into a war against the Aetolian League, which was called the "Social War".
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The young king Philip V of Macedon sided with the Achaeans and called for a Panhellenic conference in Corinth, where the Aetolian aggression was condemned.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] After Aratus's death, however, the League joined Rome in the Second Macedonian War (200–196 BC), which broke Macedonian power in mainland Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The Achaean League was one of the main beneficiaries.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Under the leadership of Philopoemen, the League was able to finally defeat a heavily weakened Sparta and take control of the entire Peloponnese.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The League's dominance was not to last long, however.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] In 146 BC, the league's relations with Rome completely collapsed, leading to the Achaean War.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The Romans under Lucius Mummius defeated the Achaeans at the Battle of Corinth, razed Corinth and dissolved the League, finally putting an end to the independence of Ancient Greece from external rule and ushering in the Roman era.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Griffith has written that Achaean War was "a hopeless enterprise for the Achaeans, badly led and backed by no adequate reserves of money or men." Lucius Mummius received the agnomen *Achaicus* ("conqueror of Achaea") for his role.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The original name Koinon of Achaeans (Achaean League) continues to exist in epigraphy, denoting either the previous Peloponnesian members (see koinon of Free Laconians) or the whole of Roman Achaea.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] 120 BC Achaeans of cities in the Peloponnese dedicated an honorary inscription to Olympian Zeus, after a military expedition with Gnaeus Domitius against the Galatians in Gallia Transalpina.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The government of the league consisted of an assembly of citizens, a smaller council, and a *strategos* (general).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The *strategos* (general) controlled the league's military forces.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Originally, two *strategoi* held office simultaneously, but from 251, there was only one, who was elected annually by the assembly.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Until 217 the *strategos* entered office in May; afterwards he assumed power at the beginning of winter.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Individuals could hold the office more than once (and frequently did so), but not in consecutive years.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The general was assisted in his duties by a board of ten *demiourgoi*, a secretary, a *hipparch* (cavalry commander), a *navarch* (admiral), and *hypostrategoi* (sub-generals commanding in military districts).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The office of *Hegemon* (leader) was given to various Antigonid and Ptolemaic kings at various points in Achaean history.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Ostensibly, the *hegemon* had ultimate command on land and sea, but in fact the office seems to have been an honorary position which obliged the holder to contribute money to the League and support the League's military ventures.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Ultimate decision-making power rested with the assembly (*synodos*), which was held at Aegium four times a year.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] All male citizens of communities belonging to the League were entitled to attend.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Alongside the assembly there was a council (*boule*), which was open to citizen men over thirty years old.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Special meetings (*synkletoi*) had to be called in order for the league to declare war, form an alliance, or receive official communications from the Macedonian king or (later) the Roman Republic.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The league was ostensibly a democracy, but control seems to have consistently rested with a small elite group who monopolised the generalship and other official positions.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Given the difficulty of travelling to Aegium, assemblies were probably dominated by the wealthy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The Achaean army was an army of the traditional *hoplite* type.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] From the 270s onwards however, much like the rest of Greece, the emergence of the shield known as the *thyreos* was incorporated into Greek warfare and a new type of troop was developed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Reforming their troops into *thyreophoroi*, the Achaean army was now composed of light troops.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The *thyreophoroi* were a mixture of evolved *peltasts* and light *hoplites*, carrying the *thureos* shield, a thrusting spear and javelins.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Plutarch says that they could be effective at a distance, but in close combat the narrow *thureos* shield disadvantaged them.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] He also says that their formation was ineffective, because it lacked inter-locked shields or a 'leveled line of spears'.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Aratus, one of the major Achaean *strategoi* (generals) and statesmen was known for his use of light forces for irregular operations, a type of warfare suited to the *thyreophoroi* but not suited to operations in the open field.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The League in 217 decided to maintain a standing force of 8,000 mercenary foot and 500 mercenary cavalry, added to a picked citizen force of 3,000 infantry and 300 cavalry, of which 500 foot and 50 horse would come from Argos and the same amount from Megalopolis.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Aratus also obtained 500 foot and 50 horse each from Taurion and the Messenians for defence of parts of the League open to attack via Laconia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The citizen infantry would have been armed as *thyreophoroi*, apart from the citizen light troops who would have been archers and slingers etc.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] This picked citizen force may well have existed before these so-called reforms, at least on an official basis, as we know of a similar elite force of the same size at the Battle of Sellasia in 222.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] However, it was the Achaean general Philopoemen in 208 who changed the Achaean fighting style and weaponry to the Macedonian fashion.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] According to Plutarch, Philopoemen 'persuaded them to adopt long pike and heavy shield instead of spear and buckler, to protect their bodies with helmets and breastplates and greaves, and to practice stationary and steadfast fighting instead of the nimble movements of light-armed troops'.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] These 'reforms' were not necessarily new to some of the constituent cities of the League, as the city of Megalopolis had been given bronze shields and armed in the Macedonian fashion by Antigonus Doson for the Sellasia campaign many years before.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Philopoemen then trained the new army how to fight with the new weapons and tactics and how to co-ordinate them with a new mercenary corps that was hired.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] He spent nearly 8 months of his term as *strategos* visiting, training and advising cities in this capacity.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] At the Battle of Mantinea in 207 BC the Achaean phalanx was positioned with intervals between the companies with lighter troops.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] This was a major attempt by Philopoemen to increase the flexibility of his phalanx.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] He may have picked up this tactic too from his experience at the Battle of Sellasia, where the phalanx of Antigonus Doson was also divided up with light/medium troops in between them.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] As well as reforming and re-organizing the infantry, Philopoemen also reformed the citizen cavalry.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The cavalry was recruited, much like in other Greek states, from the rich and noble classes.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Philopoemen organized the cavalry in *lochoi*, which usually in ancient military treatises means 'files', most probably of 8 men, grouped into *dilochiai*, a formation of double-files of 16 and so forth.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] However, by the time of the Achaean War in 146 BC, the League's army had decreased in strength and efficiency.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The League was even reduced to freeing and arming 12,000 slaves.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] This was probably due to the 2nd century BC decline in population.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] This may well account for the increased hiring of mercenaries, especially Cretans and Thracians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The below are the original Peloponnesian members, except the ancient regions of Sparta, Elis and Messenia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Later Hypana in Elis, Corone, Messene, Sparta and Pagae in Attica were joined by conquest.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] In 223 BC, Megara in Attica deserted the Achaean League and joined the Boeotian Confederacy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Besides many city-states on the Mainland joining the Achaean Federation, certain Mediterranean island city-states also became part of the federation.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] For example, Kydonia on Crete joined at some time after 219 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The city of Helike had been an important member of the first Achaean League, but sank into the sea following a disastrous earthquake in 373 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The town of Olenus, also one of the twelve members of the first Achaean League, had been abandoned before 280 BC, but was sometimes counted as though still extant.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] The dates in brackets indicate the year of first adhesion.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-league] Some cities had periods of separation or foreign occupation and later joined again.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The **Achaean War** of 146 BC was fought between the Roman Republic and the Greek Achaean League, an alliance of Achaean and other Peloponnesian states in ancient Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] It was the final stage of Rome's conquest of mainland Greece, taking place just after the Fourth Macedonian War.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Tensions rose dramatically in 148 BC, when Achaea defeated and finally subjugated Sparta; in the aftermath of this, Rome tried to cow the League into halting its expansionist ambitions, but a failure of diplomacy between the two sides led to war.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Rome swiftly defeated the League's main force near Scarpheia, before advancing on the League's capital of Corinth, where they defeated the remnants of the Achaean forces outside the walls and then brutally sacked the city, the same year in which they destroyed Carthage.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The war marked the beginning of direct Roman control of Greece, and the end of Greek independence, as well as the beginning of the end of the Hellenistic period.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] It is also noted for its significant cultural impact on Rome; the preponderance of Greek art, culture and slaves in the aftermath of the conquest accelerated the development of Greco-Roman culture.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The Roman Republic had developed close ties to the Achaean League through similar religious and military beliefs and a cooperation in the previous Macedonian Wars.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] However, despite co-operation in the latter part of the third century and early second century, political problems in Achaea soon came to a head.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Achaea was, in addition, undergoing internal pressures beyond the question over the nature of the influence of Rome.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The withdrawal of Messene from the Achaean League and further disputes with Sparta over the nature of its position in the League led to growing amounts of micromanagement by the Romans, including the sending in 184 of a Roman, Appius Claudius, to judge the case between Sparta and Achaea.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The sending of no fewer than five Achaean embassies to Rome seeking the return of the hostages, and Roman intransigence to Achaean concerns, demonstrate the power difference between the two.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The diplomatic stand-off would trigger a chain of events that ultimately led to the Achaean War.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Achaean domestic politics at the time played a large part in the coming about of the war.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] An uprising around this time by the pretender Andriscus in the Fourth Macedonian War may also have spread to Achaea, giving hope that Rome, engaged in the Third Punic War to the West, would be too busy to deal with Greek rebellions against Roman rule.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] In 150 BC, hostilities between Sparta and the League flared up again; Sparta demanded more autonomy, and revolted when this was refused.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The Acheans swiftly defeated Sparta, but the League's *strategos* of 149, Damocritus, decided not to press the offensive further, either due to Roman pressure or a policy of pacifism.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] This was unpopular, and resulted in his exile.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The *strategos* of 148, Diaeus, was elected on a platform of aggression and League unity, and hence swiftly pressed home the attack, and subjugated Sparta by the end of the year.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] During this war, Rome did not intervene beyond sending a few mild requests for peace, as the Fourth Macedonian War and the Third Punic War had become serious, requiring their attention.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] In 147, however, Rome sent a fresh embassy, led by former consul Lucius Aurelius Orestes.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Orestes tried to announce the forced reduction of the Achaean League to its original, narrow grouping - effectively crippling it and ending its territorial ambitions once and for all.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] This may have been an attempted negotiation tactic, but it backfired, and the embassy was almost mobbed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] A Roman effort at restoring peace, led by Orestes' former co-consul Sextus Julius Caesar, went badly, and the Achaeans, outraged at Rome's actions, and whipping up populist sentiment, declared war on Sparta, electing Critolaos as *strategos* of the league.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] There is debate as to how this declaration sparked the war: whether it was an implicit declaration against Rome as well, or Rome reacted to the declaration.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The Achaeans were aware that they were entering a suicidal war of defiance, as Rome had just soundly conquered Macedon, a much more powerful kingdom.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Two Roman armies were sent to put down the uprising - one under Mummius, who was now consul, sent from Italy, and the other under praetor Quintus Caecilius Metellus Macedonicus, who had recently defeated Andriscus and put down the Macedonian uprising.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Critolaos was besieging Heraclea in Trachis, which had rebelled from the League, when he learnt that Metellus was marching from Macedonia to fight him.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] He retreated to Scarpheia, but Metellus caught up with him and decisively defeated him at the Battle of Scarpheia, after which he put his army into winter quarters.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Critolaos died during or after the battle, either drowning in the marshes of Mount Oeta or poisoning himself.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The defeat and death of Critolaos caused great confusion and panic in the Greek world, with some cities such as Elis and Messene now surrendering to the Romans.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] However, many elements of the League, especially Corinth, rallied around Diaeus, electing him as *strategos* to replace Critolaos and resolving to continue the war, with harsh levies and confiscations of property and wealth.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Metellus now advanced through Boeotia, capturing Thebes, which had been allied to the Achaeans.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] He made an offer of peace to the League, but was rebuffed by Diaeus, who also had pro-peace and pro-Roman politicians arrested or killed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Mummius now arrived, and after ordering Metellus back to Macedonia, gathered all available Roman forces - 23,000 infantry and 3,500 cavalry - for an assault on Corinth.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Diaeus also rallied what forces he could, amounting to 13,500 infantry and 650 cavalry.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] After success in an initial skirmish, Diaeus gained confidence and decided to engage the Romans directly in battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] In the ensuing Battle of Corinth, however, his inferior cavalry was quickly driven off by the Roman cavalry.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] This exposed his flank to an attack by 1,000 picked Roman infantry, routing his army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Diaeus abandoned his troops and fled to Megalopolis, where he committed suicide after killing his wife.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Demoralized, the surviving Achaean troops and most Corinthians fled the city, leaving it defenseless, allowing the Romans to secure it, though only three days after the battle, as Mummius feared an ambush.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Any remaining Greek holdouts now surrendered.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The consul granted freedom to all Greeks, except the Corinthians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] In Corinth, however, the Romans massacred the entire adult male population and enslaved all the women and children, after which they destroyed the city.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] This apparently needless display of cruelty in Corinth, is explained by Mommsen as due to the instructions of the Senate, prompted by the mercantile party, which was eager to dispel a dangerous commercial rival.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] According to Polybius, Mummius was unable to resist the pressure of those around him.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] According to Dio, Mummius took care not to enslave any non-Corinthians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Livy writes that Mummius did not appropriate any of the spoils for himself, and praises him for his integrity.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Polybius mentions the carelessness of Roman soldiers, who destroyed works of art or treated them like objects of entertainment.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] However, they did show respect to the statues of Philopoemen, both for his fame and as he was the first ally of Rome in Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Mummius was extremely ignorant in matters of art - when transporting priceless statues and paintings to Italy, he gave orders that the contractors should be warned that if they lost them, they would have to replace them by new ones.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] In the immediate aftermath of the conquest, Mummius ordered the walls of all cities that had taken part in the revolt to be torn down, and forced all cities to hand over their weapons and military equipment.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Soon, the senate dispatched ten commissioners to Achaea to aid the consul in the task of reorganising Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The Greeks had to pay war indemnities and tributes, all leagues and other political entities were dissolved, and power was given to pro-Roman elites.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Eventually, however, some financial relief was given, and autonomy was granted to some cities, including Athens and Sparta.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Politically, the Greek states were grouped into the Roman province of Macedonia, though Achaea would become a separate province under Augustus in 27 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Mummius celebrated a triumph and gained the agnomen *Achaicus*.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] With wealth from his Greek campaigns, he erected a theatre with improved acoustical conditions and seats after the Greek model, thus marking a distinct advance in the construction of places of entertainment.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The war marked the end of Greek political independence, and the beginning of the end of the Hellenistic period.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Pergamon, the only significant remaining power in the Aegean, was generally pro-Roman, and its last king, Attalus III, bequeathed it to Rome through his will upon his death in 133 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] Thus, seventy years after Rome was first involved in Greek affairs in the First Macedonian War, it was now in control of all of the classical Greek world, and had cemented its position as the dominant power in the Mediterranean.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/achaean-war] The annexation would also mark the beginning of a new, Greco-Roman culture, as Greek and Roman culture intermingled, a process that had begun in the wake of the conquest of Magna Graecia by the Romans more than a century before.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Warfare occurred throughout the history of Ancient Greece, from the Greek Dark Ages onward.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Greek Dark Ages drew to an end as a significant increase in population allowed urbanized culture to be restored, which led to the rise of the city-states (poleis).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] These developments ushered in the period of Archaic Greece (800–480 BC).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] They also restored the capability of organized warfare between these *poleis* (as opposed to small-scale raids to acquire livestock and grain, for example).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The fractious nature of Ancient Greek society seems to have made continuous conflict on this larger scale inevitable.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Along with the rise of the city-state evolved a new style of warfare: the hoplite phalanx.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Hoplites were armored infantrymen, armed with spears and shields.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Seen in media, the phalanx was a formation of these soldiers with their shields locked together and spears pointed forward.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Chigi vase, dated to around 650 BC, is the earliest depiction of a hoplite in full battle array.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] With this evolution in warfare, battles seem to have consisted mostly of the clash of hoplite phalanxes from the city-states in conflict.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Since the soldiers were citizens with other occupations, warfare was limited in distance, season and scale.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Neither side could afford heavy casualties or sustained campaigns, so conflicts seem to have been resolved by a single set-piece battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The scope and scale of warfare in Ancient Greece changed as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars, which marked the beginning of Classical Greece (480–323 BC).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] To battle the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of many city-states, on a scale and scope never seen before.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The rise of the naval power of Athens in competition with the dominant land power of Sparta after this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw diversification of warfare.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Emphasis shifted to naval battles and strategies of attrition such as blockades and sieges.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Following the defeat of the Athenians in 404 BC, and the disbandment of the Athenian-dominated Delian League, Ancient Greece fell under the Spartan hegemony.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] But this was unstable, and the Persian Empire sponsored a rebellion by the combined powers of Athens, Thebes, Corinth and Argos, resulting in the Corinthian War (395–387 BC).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Persia switched sides, which ended the war, in return for the cities of Ionia and Spartan non-inter­ference in Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Spartan hegemony would last another 16 years, until, at the Battle of Leuctra (371 BC) the Spartans were decisively defeated by the Theban general Epaminondas.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Thebans acted with alacrity to establish a hegemony of their own over Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, Thebes lacked sufficient manpower and resources, and became overstretched.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Following the death of Epaminondas and loss of manpower at the Battle of Mantinea, the Theban hegemony ceased.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The losses in the ten years of the Theban hegemony left all the Greek city-states weakened and divided.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The city-states of southern Greece were now too weak to resist the rise of the Macedonian kingdom under Philip II.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] With revolutionary tactics and a reformed Macedonian army, Philip II of Macedon brought most of Greece under his sway, paving the way for the conquest of "the known world" by his son Alexander the Great.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The rise of the Macedon marked the end of the distinctive hoplite battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Along with the rise of the city-state evolved a brand new style of warfare and the emergence of the hoplite.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The hoplite was an infantryman, the central element of warfare in Ancient Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The word hoplite (Greek ὁπλίτης, hoplitēs) derives from hoplon (ὅπλον, plural hopla, ὅπλα) meaning the arms carried by a hoplite Hoplites were the citizen-soldiers of the Ancient Greek city-states (except Spartans who were professional soldiers).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] They were primarily armed as spearmen and fought in a phalanx (see below).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Hoplite armor was extremely expensive for the average citizen, so it was commonly passed down from the soldier's father or relative.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Alexander's Macedonian army had spears called sarissas that were 5+1⁄2 metres (18 feet) long, far longer than the 2–3 m (6–9 ft) Greek dory.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The secondary weapon of a hoplite was the xiphos, a short sword used when the soldier's spear was broken or lost while fighting.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The origins of the hoplite are obscure, and no small matter of contention amongst historians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Traditionally, this has been dated to the 8th century BC, and attributed to Sparta; but more recent views suggest a later date, towards the 7th century BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Certainly, by approximately 650 BC, as dated by the Chigi vase, the "hoplite revolution" was complete.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The major innovation in the development of the hoplite seems to have been the characteristic circular shield (*aspis*), roughly 1 m (3 ft) in diameter, and made of wood faced with bronze.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although comparatively heavy, the design of this shield was such that it could be supported on the shoulder.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] More importantly, it permitted the formation of a shield-wall by an army, an impenetrable mass of men and shields.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Men were also equipped with metal greaves and also a breastplate made of bronze, leather, or stiff cloth.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] When this was combined with the primary weapon of the hoplite, the 2–3 m (6–9 ft) long spear (the *doru*), it gave both offensive and defensive capabilities.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Regardless of where it developed, the model for the hoplite army evidently quickly spread throughout Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The persuasive qualities of the phalanx were probably its relative simplicity (allowing its use by a citizen militia), low fatality rate (important for small city-states), and relatively low cost (enough for each hoplite to provide his own equipment).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The phalanx also became a source of political influence because men had to provide their own equipment to be a part of the army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The ancient Greek city-states developed a military formation called the phalanx, which were rows of shoulder-to-shoulder hoplites.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The hoplites would lock their shields together, and the first few ranks of soldiers would project their spears out over the first rank of shields.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The phalanx therefore presented a shield wall and a mass of spear points to the enemy, making frontal assaults much more difficult.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] It also allowed a higher proportion of the soldiers to be actively engaged in combat at a given time (rather than just those in the front rank).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The phalanx formed the core of ancient Greek militaries.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Because hoplites were all protected by their own shield and others' shields and spears, they were relatively safe as long as the formation didn't break.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] When advancing towards an enemy, the phalanx would break into a run that was sufficient to create momentum but not too much as to lose cohesion.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The opposing sides would collide viciously, possibly terrifying many of the hoplites of the front row.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The battle would then rely on the valour of the men in the front line, while those in the rear maintained forward pressure on the front ranks with their shields.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] When in combat, the whole formation would consistently press forward trying to break the enemy formation; thus, when two phalanx formations engaged, the struggle essentially became a pushing match, in which, as a rule, the deeper phalanx would almost always win, with few recorded exceptions.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] When exactly the phalanx was developed is uncertain, but it is thought to have been developed by the Argives in their early clashes with the Spartans.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The hoplite was a well-armed and armored citizen-soldier primarily drawn from the middle classes.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Every man had to serve at least two years in the army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Fighting in the tight phalanx formation maximised the effectiveness of his armor, large shield and long spear, presenting a wall of armor and spear points to the enemy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] At least in the Archaic Period, the fragmentary nature of Ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict, but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their citizens to fight.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their jobs (especially in the case of farmers).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Armies marched directly to their target, possibly agreed on by the protagonists.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Sparta was an exception to this rule, as every Spartiate was a professional soldier.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Spartans instead relied on slaves called helots for civilian jobs such as farming.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] If battle was refused by one side, it would retreat to the city, in which case the attackers generally had to content themselves with ravaging the countryside around, since the campaign season was too limited to attempt a siege.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] When battles occurred, they were usually set-piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] These battles were short, bloody, and brutal, and thus required a high degree of discipline.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] At least in the early classical period, hoplites were the primary force; light troops and cavalry generally protected the flanks and performed skirmishing, acting as support troops for the core heavy infantry.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The strength of hoplites was shock combat.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The two phalanxes would smash into each other in hopes of quickly breaking the enemy force's line.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Failing that, a battle degenerated into a pushing match, with the men in the rear trying to force the front lines through those of the enemy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This maneuver was known as the othismos or "push".
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Thucydides described hoplite warfare as *othismos aspidon* or "the push of shields".
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Battles rarely lasted more than an hour.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Once one of the lines broke, the troops would generally flee from the field, chased by peltasts or light cavalry if available.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] If a hoplite escaped, he would sometimes be forced to drop his cumbersome aspis, thereby disgracing himself to his friends and family.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, amounting to anywhere between 5% and 15% for the winning and losing sides respectively, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Thus, the whole war could be decided by a single field battle; victory was enforced by ransoming the dead back to the defeated, called the "Custom of the Dead Greeks"..
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Greek armies also included significant numbers of light infantry, the *psiloi*, as support troops for the heavy hoplites, who also doubled as baggage handlers for the heavy foot.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] These included javelin throwers (*akontistai*), stone throwers (*lithoboloi* and *petroboloi*) and slingers (*sphendonitai*) while archers (*toxotai*) were rare, mainly from Crete, or mercenary non-Greek tribes (as at the crucial Battle of Plataea (479 BC)).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Greek armies gradually downgraded the armor of the hoplites (to linen padded thorax and open helmets) to make the phalanx more flexible and upgraded the javelineers to lightly-armored general-purpose infantry (*thorakitai* and *thyreophoroi*) with javelins and sometimes spears.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Eventually, these types effectively complemented the Macedonian‐style phalanx which prevailed throughout Greece after Alexander the Great.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Cavalry had always existed in Greek armies of the classical era but the cost of horses made it far more expensive than hoplite armor, limiting cavalrymen to nobles and the very wealthy (social class of *hippeis*).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] During the early hoplite era cavalry played almost no role whatsoever, mainly for social, but also tactical reasons, since the middle-class phalanx completely dominated the battlefield.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Gradually, and especially during the Peloponnesian War, cavalry became more important acquiring every role that cavalry could play, except perhaps frontal attack.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] It scouted, screened, harassed, outflanked and pursued with the most telling moment being the use of Syracusan horse to harass and eventually destroy the retreating Athenian army of the disastrous Sicilian expedition 415-413 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] One of the most famous troop of Greek cavalry was the Tarantine cavalry, originating from the city-state of Taras in Magna Graecia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Though ancient Greek historians made little mention of mercenaries, archeological evidence suggests that troops defending Himera were not strictly Greek in ancestry.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Though the victory at Himera is widely seen as a defining event for Greek identity, analysis of the DNA of 54 corpses found in graves unearthed in Himera's west necropolis traced professional soldiers to regions near modern Ukraine, Latvia, and Bulgaria.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Campaigns were often timed with the agricultural season to impact the enemy's or enemies' crops and harvest.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The timing had to be carefully arranged so that the invaders' enemy's harvest would be disrupted, but the invaders' harvest would not be affected.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Late invasions were also possible in the hopes that the sowing season would be affected, but this, at best, would have minimal effects on the harvest.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] One alternative to disrupting the harvest was to ravage the countryside by uprooting trees, burning houses and crops, and killing all who were not safe behind the walls of the city.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Uprooting trees was especially effective given the Greek reliance on the olive crop and the long time it takes new olive trees to reach maturity.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Ravaging the countryside took much effort and depended on the season because green crops do not burn as well as those nearer to harvest.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] War also led to the acquisition of land and enslaved people, which would lead to a greater harvest that could support a larger army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Plunder was also a large part of the war, and this allowed for pressure to be taken off of the government finances and allowed for investments to be made that would strengthen the polis.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] War also stimulated production because of the sudden demand for weapons and armor.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Shipbuilders would also experience sudden increases in their production demands.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] In open sea, the Greek navy would sail in an upside-down ship formation, led by the commander's ship.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, at first sight of enemy ships, the Greek navy would turn to starboard or port to form its line for battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The battle line consisted of ships lined up side by side, facing the enemy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This abreast formation acted as both an offensive and defensive tactic.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Offensively, it allowed the ancient ships' main weapon, the ram, to be easily accessible.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] With the entire fleet alongside each other, there were more rams available to attack the opponent.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This formation also provided the Greek fleet with protection by shielding the most vulnerable parts of the ships, which were the sides and the stern.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The abreast formation was used in almost all of the naval battles, except during the Battle of Naupactus.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] During this battle, the Athenian navy was attacked before it could transition into its battle formation.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This battle formation was also so successful for the Greek navy that their opponents began to utilize it as well.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] In order to continue being successful, the Greek navy had to create new tactics and technology to be able to conquer its opponents.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The *diekplous* was an ancient Greek naval operation used to infiltrate the enemy's line-of-battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The maneuver consisted of Greek ships, in line abreast, rowing through gaps between its enemy's ships.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] After the galley successfully crossed the opponent's line, the Greek ships would turn around and attack the susceptible side of the opponent's vessel.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although the *diekplous* is considered to be one of the most effective maneuvers in naval warfare, it was only successfully used in three battles: Lade, Chios, and Side.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] One reason why the tactic became less useful was that enemies quickly developed defensive tactics against it.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] One way opponents countered the *diekplous* was by retreating their fleet into a tight circle with the prows of their ships facing outward.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This defensive maneuver was known as the hedgehog counter-formation.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The tight circle prevented the Greek navy from infiltrating its opponent's squadron because if the navy used the *diekplous*, the galley would be encircled by its enemy and rammed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This counter formation was used by Themistocles in the Battle of Artemisium.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Another naval tactic used by the ancient Greeks was the *periplous.* The *periplous* consisted of the Greek navy "sailing around" the enemy's line.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Like the *diekplous*, the *periplous'* purpose was to expose the enemy's stern for an easy ramming target.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] An example of this tactic is described by Thucydides during the second battle between the Athenians and Peloponnesians in the Gulf of Corinth.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] During this engagement, a single Athenian galley was being pursued by a Peloponnesian ship until the Athenian ship circled around a merchant ship and rammed the Peloponnesian vessel and sank it.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Athenian ship was successful in this maneuver because it was the faster of the two ships, which is a key element in the *periplous*.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The ram on the trireme was the Greek navy's most successful weapon.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] A trireme was equipped with a large piece of timber sheathed in an envelope of bronze, located in the front of the ship.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although each ship had a ram, the ship needed to have a skilled crew to be successful with this tactic.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The oarsman rowing the ship needed to accurately hit the target, and then be able to quickly dislodge the weapon before the enemy ship sank.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The usual target during this attack was the stern, where the steering oars were located, or the side of the ship where the rowing oars were.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] While the ramming itself may have caused only a few casualties to the enemy, the majority of the casualties occurred later as the vessel began to sink, forcing its crew into the water.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] During an attack using the ram, the crew also sheared the enemy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Shearing occurred when the oars of one ship collided with any part of the opposing ship.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] During the collision, the wooden paddles shattered and often skewered the rower and the men surrounding him.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] In addition to maiming, if not immediately killing, the enemy, the attacker was given another advantage to ram the opponent.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This opportunity occurred while the attacked vessel stopped rowing to evaluate the strength of each side of oarsman, leaving it in a standstill.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The temporarily inoperative ship would become victim to more ramming and spearing attacks.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Marines, or *epibatai*, were the secondary weapon for the Greek navy after the ram.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] During battles, marines were responsible for both attacking the enemy's ship, and preventing their own ship from being boarded.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The number of marines on the trireme fluctuated based on each battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] For example, during the Peloponnesian War, there were 4 archers and 10 marines on the deck of a vessel.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, Cimon had forty marines aboard each ship during the battle of Eurymedon.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The difference in numbers between these two battles is because commanders used the marines for different purposes based on the circumstance of the battles.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] If the battle was being fought in confined waters, there would be more marines on the trireme.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The ships would require more marines because the constricted water would prevent the use of typical tactics, and would increase the risk of the ship being boarded by the enemy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Archers were also important in naval battles.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The arrows of the seagoing archers were deadly and efficient and could decrease the enemy's fighting power considerably by picking off officers and men on the enemy ship.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The arrows had an effective range of 160–170 meters.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] When fired from a ship executing a *diekplous* or a ramming blow, the arrows had a greater velocity.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Soldiers of the Greek army were called hoplites.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] They were known for their courage and strength.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Stories like the Battle of Thermopylae demonstrate the strength and skill Greeks had in land battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] From the moment Greeks started fighting with "bronze shields and in the *phalanx*," they must have regularly been drawn up in rank and file and not just crowded together.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] They had a specific formation in order to execute all of their military maneuvers.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Athenian army was typically divided into ten *taxeis*, or tribal regiments, and subdivided into *lochoi*.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] These subunits worked as smaller pieces of an overall picture of military power.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Trained thoroughly, the hoplites were as skilled at their melee combat as the Athenian oarsmen were at their precision ramming and rowing.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The phalanx was an army tactic the Greeks performed with shields.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Each soldier carried a shield in his left arm, which he used to protect both himself and the man on his left.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The depth of the phalanx differed depending on the battle and commander, but the width of the formation was considerably greater than its depth.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] For example, during the battle of Syracuse, the depth of the Athenian army's phalanx was 8 men, while its opponent, the Syracusan army, had a depth of 16 men.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Melee, or hand-to-hand combat, occurred most often after the tight formation of the phalanx dispersed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This fighting was also often referred to as dorarismos, meaning "spear-fighting" because the hoplites would use small swords in the fighting.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] One example of melee combat is described by Herodotus during a battle at Thermopylae.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] An uncommon tactic of Ancient Greek warfare, during the hoplite battles, was the use of ambush.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] When light-armed forces began to be used, ambushing became a recognized scheme.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The most known version of this tactic occurred during the Battle of Dyme in 218 BC, when one side pretended to retreat from the fighting and enticed their enemy to follow them into an ambush.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This tactic became so well known that in 217 BC the Stratian army declined to pursue the Akarnanians during their retreat in fear that they would face an ambush.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The scale and scope of warfare in Ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of many city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labour.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although alliances between city states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Greco-Persian Wars (499–448 BC) were the result of attempts by the Persian Emperor Darius the Great, and then his successor Xerxes I to subjugate Ancient Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Darius was already ruler of the cities of Ionia, and the wars are taken to start when they rebelled in 499 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The revolt was crushed by 494 BC, but Darius resolved to bring mainland Greece under his dominion.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Many city-states made their submission to him, but others did not, notably including Athens and Sparta.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Darius thus sent his commanders Datis and Artaphernes to attack Attica, to punish Athens for her intransigence.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] After burning Eretria, the Persians landed at Marathon.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] 10,000 hoplites marched to meet the Persian army of about 25,000 troops.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Athenians were at a significant disadvantage both strategically and tactically.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Raising such a large army had denuded Athens of defenders, and thus any attack in the Athenian rear would cut off the Army from the City.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Tactically, the hoplites were very vulnerable to attacks by cavalry, and the Athenians had no cavalry to defend the flanks.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] After several days of stalemate at Marathon, the Persian commanders attempted to take strategic advantage by sending their cavalry (by ship) to raid Athens itself.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This gave the Athenian army a small window of opportunity to attack the remainder of the Persian Army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This was the first true engagement between a hoplite army and a non-Greek army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Persians had acquired a reputation for invincibility, but the Athenian hoplites proved crushingly superior in the ensuing infantry battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] To counter the massive numbers of Persians, the Greek general Miltiades ordered the troops to be spread across an unusually wide front, leaving the centre of the Greek line undermanned.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, the lightly armored Persian infantry proved no match for the heavily armored hoplites, and the Persian wings were quickly routed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Greek wings then turned against the elite troops in the Persian centre, which had held the Greek centre until then.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Marathon demonstrated to the Greeks the lethal potential of the hoplite, and firmly demonstrated that the Persians were not, after all, invincible.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The revenge of the Persians was postponed 10 years by internal conflicts in the Persian Empire, until Darius's son Xerxes returned to Greece in 480 BC with a staggeringly large army (modern estimates suggest between 150,000 and 250,000 men).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Many Greeks city-states, having had plenty of warning of the forthcoming invasion, formed an anti-Persian league; though as before, other city-states remained neutral or allied with Persia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although alliances between city-states were commonplace, the scale of this league was a novelty, and the first time that the Greeks had united in such a way to face an external threat.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This allowed diversification of the allied armed forces, rather than simply mustering a very large hoplite army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The visionary Athenian politician Themistocles had successfully persuaded his fellow citizens to build a huge fleet in 483/82 BC to combat the Persian threat (and thus to effectively abandon their hoplite army, since there were not men enough for both).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Amongst the allies therefore, Athens was able to form the core of a navy, whilst other cities, including Sparta, provided the army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This alliance thus removed the constraints on the type of armed forces that the Greeks could use.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The use of such a large navy was also a novelty to the Greeks.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The second Persian invasion is famous for the battles of Thermopylae and Salamis.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] As the massive Persian army moved south through Greece, the allies sent a small holding force (c.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] 10,000) men under the Spartan king Leonidas, to block the pass of Thermopylae whilst the main allied army could be assembled.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The allied navy extended this blockade at sea, blocking the nearby straits of Artemisium, to prevent the huge Persian navy landing troops in Leonidas's rear.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Famously, Leonidas's men held the much larger Persian army at the pass (where their numbers were less of an advantage) for three days, the hoplites again proving their superiority.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Greek navy, despite their lack of experience, also proved their worth holding back the Persian fleet whilst the army still held the pass.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Thermopylae provided the Greeks with time to arrange their defences, and they dug in across the Isthmus of Corinth, an impregnable position; although an evacuated Athens was thereby sacrificed to the advancing Persians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] In order to outflank the isthmus, Xerxes needed to use this fleet, and in turn therefore needed to defeat the Greek fleet; similarly, the Greeks needed to neutralise the Persian fleet to ensure their safety.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] To this end, the Greeks were able to lure the Persian fleet into the straits of Salamis; and, in a battleground where Persian numbers again counted for nothing, they won a decisive victory, justifying Themistocles' decision to build the Athenian fleet.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Demoralised, Xerxes returned to Asia Minor with much of his army, leaving his general Mardonius to campaign in Greece the following year (479 BC).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] 40,000 hoplites decisively defeated Mardonius at the Battle of Plataea, effectively ending the invasion.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Almost simultaneously, the allied fleet defeated the remnants of the Persian navy at Mycale, thus destroying the Persian hold on the islands of the Aegean.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The remainder of the wars saw the Greeks take the fight to the Persians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Athenian dominated Delian League of cities and islands extirpated Persian garrisons from Macedon and Thrace, before eventually freeing the Ionian cities from Persian rule.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] At one point, the Greeks even attempted an invasion of Cyprus and Egypt (which proved disastrous), demonstrating a major legacy of the Persian Wars: warfare in Greece had moved beyond the seasonal squabbles between city-states, to coordinated international actions involving huge armies.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] After the war, ambitions of many Greek states dramatically increased.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Tensions resulting from this, and the rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during the war led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Peloponnesian War (431–404 BC), was fought between the Athenian dominated Delian League and the Spartan dominated Peloponnesian League.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale, and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Set-piece battles during this war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on naval warfare, and strategies of attrition such as blockades and sieges.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Whatever the proximal causes of the war, it was in essence a conflict between Athens and Sparta for supremacy in Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The war (or wars, since it is often divided into three periods) was for much of the time a stalemate, punctuated with occasional bouts of activity.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Tactically the Peloponnesian war represents something of a stagnation; the strategic elements were most important as the two sides tried to break the deadlock, something of a novelty in Greek warfare.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Building on the experience of the Persian Wars, the diversification from core hoplite warfare, permitted by increased resources, continued.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] There was increased emphasis on navies, sieges, mercenaries and economic warfare.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Far from the previously limited and formalized form of conflict, the Peloponnesian War transformed into an all-out struggle between city-states, complete with atrocities on a large scale; shattering religious and cultural taboos, devastating vast swathes of countryside and destroying whole cities.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] From the start, the mismatch in the opposing forces was clear.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Delian League (hereafter 'Athenians') were primarily a naval power, whereas the Peloponnesian League (hereafter 'Spartans') consisted of primarily land-based powers.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Athenians thus avoided battle on land, since they could not possibly win, and instead dominated the sea, blockading the Peloponnesus whilst maintaining their trade.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Conversely, the Spartans repeatedly invaded Attica, but only for a few weeks at a time; they remained wedded to the idea of hoplite-as-citizen.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although both sides suffered setbacks and victories, the first phase essentially ended in stalemate, as neither league had the power to neutralise the other.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The second phase, an Athenian expedition to attack Syracuse in Sicily achieved no tangible result other than a large loss of Athenian ships and men.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] In the third phase of the war however the use of more sophisticated stratagems eventually allowed the Spartans to force Athens to surrender.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Firstly, the Spartans permanently garrisoned a part of Attica, removing from Athenian control the silver mine which funded the war effort.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Forced to squeeze even more money from her allies, the Athenian league thus became heavily strained.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] After the loss of Athenian ships and men in the Sicilian expedition, Sparta was able to foment rebellion amongst the Athenian league, which therefore massively reduced the ability of the Athenians to continue the war.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Athens in fact partially recovered from this setback between 410 and 406 BC, but a further act of economic war finally forced her defeat.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Having developed a navy that was capable of taking on the much-weakened Athenian navy, the Spartan general Lysander seized the Hellespont, the source of Athens' grain.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The remaining Athenian fleet was thereby forced to confront the Spartans, and were decisively defeated.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Athens had little choice but to surrender; and was stripped of her city walls, overseas possessions and navy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although tactically there was little innovation in the Peloponessian War, there does appear to have been an increase in the use of light infantry, such as peltasts (javelin throwers) and archers.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Many of these would have been mercenary troops, hired from outlying regions of Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] For instance, the Agrianes from Thrace were well-renowned peltasts, whilst Crete was famous for its archers.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Since there were no decisive land-battles in the Peloponnesian War, the presence or absence of these troops was unlikely to have affected the course of the war.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Nevertheless, it was an important innovation, one which was developed much further in later conflicts.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Following the eventual defeat of the Athenians in 404 BC, and the disbandment of the Athenian-dominated Delian League, Ancient Greece fell under the hegemony of Sparta.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The peace treaty which ended the Peloponnesian War left Sparta as the *de facto* ruler of Greece (*hegemon*).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although the Spartans did not attempt to rule all of Greece directly, they prevented alliances of other Greek cities, and forced the city-states to accept governments deemed suitable by Sparta.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, from the very beginning, it was clear that the Spartan hegemony was shaky; the Athenians, despite their crushing defeat, restored their democracy but just one year later, ejecting the Sparta-approved oligarchy.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Spartans did not feel strong enough to impose their will on a shattered Athens.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Undoubtedly part of the reason for the weakness of the hegemony was a decline in the Spartan population.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This did not go unnoticed by the Persian Empire, which sponsored a rebellion by the combined powers of Athens, Thebes, Corinth and Argos, resulting in the Corinthian War (395–387 BC).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This was the first major challenge Sparta faced.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The early encounters, at Nemea and Coronea were typical engagements of hoplite phalanxes, resulting in Spartan victories.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, the Spartans suffered a large setback when their fleet was wiped out by a Persian Fleet at the Battle of Cnidus, undermining the campaign of the Spartan king Agesilaus II in Ionia.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The war petered out after 394 BC, with a stalemate punctuated with minor engagements.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] One of these is particularly notable however; at the Battle of Lechaeum, an Athenian force composed mostly of light troops (e.g. peltasts) defeated a Spartan regiment...
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Athenian general Iphicrates had his troops make repeated hit and run attacks on the Spartans, who, having neither peltasts nor cavalry, could not respond effectively.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The defeat of a hoplite army in this way demonstrates the changes in both troops and tactic which had occurred in Greek Warfare.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The war ended when the Persians, worried by the allies' successes, switched to supporting the Spartans, in return for the cities of Ionia and Spartan non-interference in Asia Minor.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This brought the rebels to terms, and restored the Spartan hegemony on a more stable footing.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The peace treaty which ended the war, effectively restored the *status quo ante bellum*, although Athens was permitted to retain some of the territory it had regained during the war.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Spartan hegemony would last another 16 years...
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The second major challenge Sparta faced was fatal to its hegemony, and even to its position as a first-rate power in Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] As the Thebans attempted to expand their influence over Boeotia, they inevitably incurred the ire of Sparta.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] After they refused to disband their army, an army of approximately 10,000 Spartans and Pelopennesians marched north to challenge the Thebans.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] At the decisive Battle of Leuctra (371 BC), the Thebans routed the allied army.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The battle is famous for the tactical innovations of the Theban general Epaminondas.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Defying convention, he strengthened the left flank of the phalanx to an unheard of depth of 50 ranks, at the expense of the centre and the right.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The centre and right were staggered backwards from the left (an 'echelon' formation), so that the phalanx advanced obliquely.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Theban left wing was thus able to crush the elite Spartan forces on the allied right, whilst the Theban centre and left avoided engagement; after the defeat of the Spartans and the death of the Spartan king, the rest of the allied army routed.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This is one of the first known examples of both the tactic of local concentration of force, and the tactic of 'refusing a flank'.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Following this victory, the Thebans first secured their power-base in Boeotia, before marching on Sparta.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] As the Thebans were joined by many erstwhile Spartan allies, the Spartans were powerless to resist this invasion.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Thebans marched into Messenia, and freed it from Sparta; this was a fatal blow to Sparta, since Messenia had provided most of the helots which supported the Spartan warrior society.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] These events permanently reduced Spartan power and prestige, and replaced the Spartan hegemony with a Theban one.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Theban hegemony would be short-lived however.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Opposition to it throughout the period 369–362 BC caused numerous clashes.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] In an attempt to bolster the Thebans' position, Epaminondas again marched on the Pelopennese in 362 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] At the Battle of Mantinea, the largest battle ever fought between the Greek city-states occurred; most states were represented on one side or the other.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Epaminondas deployed tactics similar to those at Leuctra, and again the Thebans, positioned on the left, routed the Spartans, and thereby won the battle.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, such were the losses of Theban manpower, including Epaminondas himself, that Thebes was thereafter unable to sustain its hegemony.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Conversely, another defeat and loss of prestige meant that Sparta was unable to regain its primary position in Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Ultimately, Mantinea, and the preceding decade, severely weakened many Greek states, and left them divided and without the leadership of a dominant power.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Although by the end of the Theban hegemony the cities of southern Greece were severely weakened, they might have risen again had it not been for the ascent to power of the Macedonian kingdom in northern Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Unlike the fiercely independent (and small) city-states, Macedon was a tribal kingdom, ruled by an autocratic king, and importantly, covering a larger area.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Once firmly unified, and then expanded, by Philip II, Macedon possessed the resources that enabled it to dominate the weakened and divided states in southern Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Between 356 and 342 BC Phillip conquered all city states in the vicinity of Macedon, then Thessaly and then Thrace.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Finally Phillip sought to establish his own hegemony over the southern Greek city-states, and after defeating the combined forces of Athens and Thebes, the two most powerful states, at the Battle of Chaeronea in 338 BC, succeeded.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Now unable to resist him, Phillip compelled most of the city states of southern Greece (including Athens, Thebes, Corinth and Argos; but not Sparta) to join the Corinthian League, and therefore become allied to him.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This established a lasting Macedonian hegemony over Greece, and allowed Phillip the resources and security to launch a war against the Persian Empire.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] After his assassination, this war was prosecuted by his son Alexander the Great, and resulted in the takeover of the whole Achaemenid Empire by the Macedonians.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] A united Macedonian empire did not long survive Alexander's death, and soon split into the Hellenistic kingdoms of the Diadochi (Alexander's generals).
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] However, these kingdoms were still enormous states, and continued to fight in the same manner as Phillip and Alexander's armies had.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The rise of Macedon and her successors thus sounded the death knell for the distinctive way of war found in Ancient Greece; and instead contributed to the 'superpower' warfare which would dominate the ancient world between 350 and 150 BC.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] One major reason for Phillip's success in conquering Greece was the break with Hellenic military traditions that he made.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] With more resources available, he was able to assemble a more diverse army, including strong cavalry components.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] He took the development of the phalanx to its logical completion, arming his 'phalangites' (for they were assuredly not hoplites) with a fearsome 6 m (20 ft) pike, the 'sarissa'.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Much more lightly armored, the Macedonian phalanx was not so much a shield-wall as a spear-wall.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The Macedonian phalanx was a supreme defensive formation, but was not intended to be decisive offensively; instead, it was used to pin down the enemy infantry, whilst more mobile forces, such as cavalry and hypaspists outflanked them.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] This 'combined arms' approach was furthered by the extensive use of skirmishers, such as peltasts.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Tactically, Phillip absorbed the lessons of centuries of warfare in Greece.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] He echoed the tactics of Epaminondas at Chaeronea, by not engaging his right wing against the Thebans until his left wing had routed the Athenians; thus in course outnumbering and outflanking the Thebans, and securing victory.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] Alexander's fame is in no small part due to his success as a battlefield tactician; the unorthodox gambits he used at the battles of Issus and Gaugamela were unlike anything seen in Ancient Greece before.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The battle of Hydaspes was the first battle that an army from Greece faced a large number of Indian war elephants.
[src:ancient-greek-warfare/ancient-greek-warfare] The beginning of the Hellenistic period and the Wars of the Diadochi marked the transition to the Hellenistic warfare.
